---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const tutorials = [
  {
    slug: "sp500-drawdowns",
    title: "Analyzing S&P 500 Drawdowns with R",
    description: "Use PerformanceAnalytics to identify every major market crash since 1990.",
    tag: "R Tutorial",
  },
];

const currentTutorial = tutorials[0];
---

<Layout title="Tutorials | Arkadi Avanesyan" description="Free tutorials on R programming, portfolio management, and quantitative finance.">
  <section class="pt-32 pb-6 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
      <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-8">
        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <aside class="lg:w-64 flex-shrink-0 lg:sticky lg:top-24 lg:self-start space-y-6">
          <!-- Workshop CTA (Top of sidebar) -->
          <a
            href="/workshops"
            class="block p-4 rounded-xl bg-slate-900 text-white hover:bg-slate-800 transition-colors"
          >
            <span class="text-xs text-green-400 font-medium uppercase tracking-wide">Free Workshop</span>
            <h3 class="font-semibold mt-1 mb-2">Build a Crisis-Proof Portfolio</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm mb-3">March 12 · Live · 45 min</p>
            <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-white font-medium">
              Learn more
              <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3" />
              </svg>
            </span>
          </a>

          <!-- Tutorials Nav -->
          <div>
            <h2 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-500 uppercase tracking-wide mb-4">Tutorials</h2>
            <nav class="space-y-2">
              {tutorials.map((tutorial) => (
                <a
                  href={`/tutorials#${tutorial.slug}`}
                  class="block px-4 py-3 rounded-xl bg-blue-50 border border-blue-100 text-slate-900 font-medium"
                >
                  {tutorial.title}
                </a>
              ))}
            </nav>
          </div>
        </aside>

        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="flex-1">
          <!-- Tutorial Content -->
          <article id={currentTutorial.slug} class="card">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
              <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-xl bg-blue-100 flex items-center justify-center">
                <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-blue-600" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 17h8m0 0V9m0 8l-8-8-4 4-6-6" />
                </svg>
              </div>
              <div>
                <span class="text-sm text-blue-600 font-medium">{currentTutorial.tag}</span>
                <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">{currentTutorial.title}</h1>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">
              Understanding historical drawdowns is essential for building crisis-proof portfolios. In this tutorial, you'll learn how to fetch S&P 500 data and identify every major market crash since 1990 using the <code class="bg-slate-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm">PerformanceAnalytics</code> package.
            </p>

            <!-- Step 1 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">1. Install required packages</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                We'll use <code class="bg-slate-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm">quantmod</code> for data fetching and <code class="bg-slate-100 px-2 py-0.5 rounded text-sm">PerformanceAnalytics</code> for drawdown analysis:
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>install.packages(c("quantmod", "PerformanceAnalytics"))</code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 2 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">2. Fetch S&P 500 data since 1990</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                Download historical data for SPY (S&P 500 ETF) and calculate returns:
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code>library(quantmod)
library(PerformanceAnalytics)

# Fetch S&P 500 data from 1990
getSymbols("^GSPC", src = "yahoo", from = "1990-01-01")

# Calculate daily returns from adjusted close
sp500_returns <- dailyReturn(Ad(GSPC))
colnames(sp500_returns) <- "SP500"

# Quick summary
head(sp500_returns)
tail(sp500_returns)</code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 3 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">3. Visualize the drawdown history</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                Plot the underwater chart showing all drawdowns over time:
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code># Plot drawdown chart
chart.Drawdown(sp500_returns,
               main = "S&P 500 Drawdowns Since 1990",
               colorset = "darkred")</code></pre>
              <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm mt-3">
                This shows every period where the market was below its previous peak. The deeper the red, the worse the drawdown.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 4 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">4. Extract the worst drawdowns</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                Identify the 10 largest drawdowns with their dates, depth, and recovery time:
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code># Get table of worst drawdowns
drawdowns <- table.Drawdowns(sp500_returns, top = 10)
print(drawdowns)</code></pre>
              <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm mt-3">
                This returns: From (start date), Trough (bottom date), To (recovery date), Depth (max loss), Length (days to bottom), To Trough (days to recover), and Recovery (total days underwater).
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 5 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">5. Calculate key drawdown statistics</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                Get summary statistics for risk assessment:
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code># Maximum drawdown
maxDrawdown(sp500_returns)

# Average drawdown
AverageDrawdown(sp500_returns)

# Calmar ratio (return / max drawdown)
CalmarRatio(sp500_returns)

# Pain index (average depth * duration)
PainIndex(sp500_returns)</code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- Step 6 -->
            <div class="mb-8">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">6. Identify crisis periods</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
                Filter for major crashes (drawdowns exceeding 20%):
              </p>
              <pre class="bg-slate-900 text-slate-100 rounded-xl p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm"><code># Get all drawdowns deeper than 20%
all_drawdowns <- table.Drawdowns(sp500_returns, top = 20)
major_crashes <- all_drawdowns[all_drawdowns$Depth < -0.20, ]
print(major_crashes)

# You'll see:
# - 2008 Financial Crisis: ~55% drawdown
# - 2020 COVID Crash: ~34% drawdown
# - 2000-2002 Dot-com Bust: ~49% drawdown
# - 2022 Bear Market: ~25% drawdown</code></pre>
            </div>

            <!-- What's Next -->
            <div class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-6 mt-8">
              <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">
                <strong>Key insight:</strong> The S&P 500 has experienced drawdowns exceeding 20% roughly once every 5-7 years. A crisis-proof portfolio should be designed to either survive these events or benefit from them. This is the foundation of antifragile portfolio construction.
              </p>
              <a
                href="/files/sp500-drawdowns.Rmd"
                download
                class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-slate-100 text-slate-700 font-medium rounded-lg hover:bg-slate-200 transition-colors text-sm"
              >
                <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M4 16v1a3 3 0 003 3h10a3 3 0 003-3v-1m-4-4l-4 4m0 0l-4-4m4 4V4" />
                </svg>
                Download R Script (.Rmd)
              </a>
            </div>
          </article>

          <!-- Bottom CTA -->
          <div class="mt-8 card bg-slate-900 text-white border-0 overflow-hidden">
            <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row items-center gap-8">
              <div class="lg:w-1/3 flex-shrink-0">
                <img
                  src="/Arkadi.L1.png"
                  alt="Arkadi Avanesyan"
                  class="w-full max-w-[240px] mx-auto rounded-xl"
                />
              </div>
              <div class="lg:w-2/3 text-center lg:text-left">
                <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm font-medium mb-2">Free Live Workshop — March 12, 2026</p>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">Build Your First Crisis-Proof Portfolio</h2>
                <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4">
                  Learn the framework I developed over 10 years at Goldman Sachs and Societe Generale. Understand why most portfolios fail in crashes — and how to build one that doesn't.
                </p>
                <ul class="text-slate-400 text-sm mb-6 space-y-1">
                  <li>Classify any asset as Fragile, Robust, or Antifragile</li>
                  <li>Identify structural flaws that cause panic-selling</li>
                  <li>45 minutes + live Q&A</li>
                </ul>
                <a
                  href="https://maven.com/p/62cecb/build-your-first-crisis-proof-portfolio"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-white text-slate-900 font-semibold px-6 py-3 rounded-full hover:bg-slate-100 transition-colors"
                >
                  Register Free
                  <svg class="w-5 h-5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3" />
                  </svg>
                </a>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- More Resources -->
  <section class="py-6 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto text-center">
      <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">
        Want more content? Check out my full courses.
      </p>
      <a href="/courses" class="btn-secondary">
        Browse Courses
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
